Message.Title: Foundry Process/Manufacturing "Roadmap"
Message.Msg: Looks pretty fragmented - looks like they all persue a somewhat different approach which could mean once a foundry candidate has been selected there will be no turning back. I just can't see how QCOM for example could split up business between two foundries anymore though they made a (small) commitment to UMC. Apple's $4 billion investment in Austin seems late - cranking out 28nm (gate first I suppose) in mid 13 - Apple has a product roadmap but to me it seems that product roadmap is everything but connected to a process/manufacturing roadmap. Samsung Austin has many Moto ex and they probably work very well together with Apple but and they have some autonomy but in the end the Koreans pull the strings. Months ago Apple cancelled some NAND business with Samsung and now they converting a NAND fab to logic - that kind of "planning" is as bad as it could be - it's terrible. IBM pushing SOI but it looks like foundries favor bulk - so much for IBM fab club. Fin height variability is very important and height variability is probably more stringent at 16nm or 14nm relative to 22nm. But Intel is processing megatons of silicon at 22nm and they can probably optimize fin height variation while producing @22nm hence enabling a smooth transition to 14nm. It will be far more difficult to get FinFet right from the getgo at 14nm compared to 22nm because Fin height variation is far more critical at 14/16nm compared to 22nm. It's going to be a bonanza for KLAC et al but I would not be surprised the ugly yield struggle will be a "deja vue" ... Read this IBM comment - they still have not agreed on SOI vs bulk... But because of fin height variability, there are fears that the foundries could struggle making bulk finFETs. People are just waking up to this, said Gary Patton, vice president of the Semiconductor Research and Development Center at IBM. The foundries should take a harder look at silicon-on-insulator (SOI) technology, which can reduce fin height variability, Patton said. And because there are fewer process steps with SOI-based finFETs, the traditional cost penalty associated with SOI disappears, he added. http://semimd.com/blog/tag/14nm/
